Alright, let's dive into Blue Team Labs Online! Starting with an easy one, Follina, we are given an infected zip file to analyze.

Question 1) What is the SHA1 hash value of the sample? (Format: SHA1Hash)
The password for the archive is given to us next to the download button, so extract using password "infected".
And lucky for me, I just learned all sorts of Linux commands during my time spent in the SANS Cyber Academy.
Let's open Kali and run a simple:
sha1sum sample.doc
And we get:
06727ffda60359236a8029e0b3e8a0fd11c23313

Question 2) According to VirusTotal, what is the full filetype of the provided sample? (Format: X X X X)
Well, let's meander on over to the VirusTotal website and see, shall we? If we load that file into the website, we get some nice details, conveniently in the Details pane. And a few lines down, we see a File Type line with the value: Office Open XML Document.
Boom, there we go!

Question 3) Extract the URL that is used within the sample and submit it (Format: https://x.domain.tld/path/to/something)
If we then make our way to the Relations tab, we see "Contacted URLs." Well, the longest/most specific one is  	https://www.xmlformats.com/office/word/2022/wordprocessingDrawing/RDF842l.html, so we try that as the answer and it works!

Question 4) What is the name of the XML file that is storing the extracted URL? (Format: file.name.ext)
If we go to "Bundled Files," the first one we see is:
word/_rels/document.xml.rels
So let's try the end of that one. And it works!

Question 5) The extracted URL accesses a HTML file that triggers the vulnerability to execute a malicious payload. According to the HTML processing functions, any files with fewer than <Number> bytes would not invoke the payload. Submit the <Number> (Format: Number of Bytes)
And here is where our time with VirusTotal ends. We have to resort to good ol' Google for this one (Google is your friend!).
This article here gives us some good info about the Follina vulnerability itself:
https://www.hackthebox.com/blog/cve-2022-30190-follina-explained
And tells us that "The secondary payload must surpass 4096 bytes to evade specific size checks."
So there we go: the answer is 4096.

Question 6) After execution, the sample will try to kill a process if it is already running. What is the name of this process? (Format: filename.ext)
Here we go to another site (which also would have answered the previous question, but I digress).
https://www.huntress.com/blog/microsoft-office-remote-code-execution-follina-msdt-bug
And here we find that there is a Base64 string that decodes to:
taskkill /f /im msdt.exe
So msdt.exe is the answer!

